               <head>Sharḥ-i Qaṣīdah-ʼi Fāriz̤īyah by ʿAbd al-Raḥmān Jāmī</head>
               <msContents
                  class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85089353 http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008112367">
                   <summary>A commentary on the famous <title>Qaṣīdah al-mīmīyah al-khamrīyah</title> of <persName role="ant" key="VIAF_118486738"> ʻUmar ibn
                        ʻAlī, often known as Ibn al-Fāriḍ</persName> (1181 or 1182-1235), by Nūr
                     al-Dīn ʿAbd al-Raḥmān Jāmī Hiravī (1414-92). The work was finished in Safar 875
                     (August-September 1470)</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_1281A-item1">
                     <author key="VIAF_90042997">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Nūr al-Dīn ʿAbd al-Raḥmān Jāmī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">نورالدّین عبدالرّحمان جامی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_21198">Sharḥ-i Qaṣīdah-ʼi
                        Fāriz̤īyah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">شرح قصیدۀ فارضیّه</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>Has two lacunae after folios 4 and 14. </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff. i+45+ii. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>186</height>
                              <width>121</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>137</height>
                              <width>75</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Foliated throughout in pencil. </p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <p>
                              <catchwords>Catchwords on the bottom-left corners of the verso.
                              </catchwords>
                           </p>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Slightly worm-eaten. Detached from binding with broken stitching. </p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="2" ruledLines="15">
                           <p>15 lines per page; poetry in two columns. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Fair naskh; copied in black ink, with most of the Arabic poetry which is being commented on in red.
                        </p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>(f. 1r) Notes giving the title of the work. </p>
                     <p>A folio, numbered 15 in pencil, has been inserted at the end of the work. Despite some
                        similarities, it does not belong to this codex and has red underlinings. </p>
                     <p>Miscellaneous notes throughout the codex. </p>
                     <p>(endleaves) A poem in <hi rend="italic">mustazād</hi> form (in which a short verse comes
                        after a long verse) ascribed to Rumi (beginning with هر لحظه بشکلی بت عیّار
                        برآمد/ دل برد و نهان شد) has been written obliquely (<hi rend="italic">chalīpā</hi>), together with
                        several rubais in a different hand. </p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1700" notAfter="1857">
                        <decoNote>Brown leather 18th or 19th century binding with gold onlay rectangular border. </decoNote>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Black Government of India Delhi MSS oval stamp (ff. 1r, 45r). </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
